Here's the xUnit equivalent:

```csharp
// Per-test setup → constructor; per-test teardown → IDisposable
// One-time setup/teardown → IClassFixture<T> with a shared fixture

public class DatabaseFixture : IDisposable
{
    public DatabaseFixture()  // OneTimeSetUp
    {
        Database.Initialize();
    }

    public void Dispose()  // OneTimeTearDown
    {
        Database.Cleanup();
    }
}

public class CustomerRepositoryTests : IClassFixture<DatabaseFixture>, IDisposable
{
    private readonly DbContext _context;
    private readonly CustomerRepository _repo;

    public CustomerRepositoryTests(DatabaseFixture _)  // SetUp
    {
        _context = new TestDbContext();
        _repo = new CustomerRepository(_context);
    }

    public void Dispose()  // TearDown
    {
        _context.Dispose();
    }

    [Fact]
    public void FindById_ExistingCustomer_ReturnsCustomer()
    {
        var customer = _repo.FindById(1);
        Assert.NotNull(customer);
        Assert.Equal("Alice", customer.Name);
    }
}
```

**Key mappings:**

| NUnit | xUnit |
|---|---|
| `[SetUp]` | Constructor |
| `[TearDown]` | `IDisposable.Dispose()` |
| `[OneTimeSetUp/TearDown]` | `IClassFixture<T>` + fixture class |
| `[TestFixture]` | *(not needed)* |
| `[Test]` | `[Fact]` |

The fixture is instantiated once per class and injected via the constructor. xUnit creates a **new test class instance per test**, so the constructor/Dispose naturally replicate per-test setup/teardown.

If you need async setup/teardown, implement `IAsyncLifetime` (with `InitializeAsync`/`DisposeAsync`) instead.
